00:01:52.098 --> 00:01:52.840
[LAUGHTER]

00:01:52.840 --> 00:01:54.155
[LAUGHS] That was subtle.

00:01:54.155 --> 00:01:55.280
I want you to think about--

00:01:55.280 --> 00:01:57.520
[LAUGHTER]

00:01:57.520 --> 00:01:59.020
I want you think
about these stories

00:01:59.020 --> 00:02:01.603
and, try to think about, if you
can, what they have in common.

00:02:01.603 --> 00:02:03.850
They're going to seem very,
very different to you.

00:02:03.850 --> 00:02:07.120
So this is Freddy Martinez.

00:02:07.120 --> 00:02:08.960
Freddy was physics trained.

00:02:08.960 --> 00:02:11.840
He's works in the tech
industry in Chicago.

00:02:11.840 --> 00:02:13.890
He's an activist.

00:02:13.890 --> 00:02:15.290
This is a stingray.

00:02:15.290 --> 00:02:18.772
I'm just curious, being here,
who knows what a stingray is?

00:02:18.772 --> 00:02:20.980
Everybody knows what a
stingray-- or a lot of people.

00:02:20.980 --> 00:02:22.896
So I'm going to tell the
few people who don't.

00:02:22.896 --> 00:02:23.720
We'll clue them in.

00:02:23.720 --> 00:02:25.610
So a stingray is a
cell tracking device.

00:02:25.610 --> 00:02:28.160
The police use it to figure
out where a cell phone is,

00:02:28.160 --> 00:02:30.410
or what cell phones
are in the area.

00:02:30.410 --> 00:02:32.880
It has some incredibly
important uses for policing.

00:02:32.880 --> 00:02:34.730
If you think about a kidnapping,
for example, and you've

00:02:34.730 --> 00:02:36.200
a cell phone number, and
you want to figure out

00:02:36.200 --> 00:02:37.340
where the person is--

00:02:37.340 --> 00:02:39.230
very helpful.

00:02:39.230 --> 00:02:41.240
It also, however,
can be used to record

00:02:41.240 --> 00:02:43.640
the phone numbers of
everybody that's at a protest.

00:02:43.640 --> 00:02:46.490
And that was Freddy's
interest, which was--

00:02:46.490 --> 00:02:49.670
were the Chicago police
collecting at Black Lives,

00:02:49.670 --> 00:02:52.370
for example, protests,
the cell phones of people?

00:02:52.370 --> 00:02:55.550
And he was trying to think about
a way to engineer something

00:02:55.550 --> 00:02:57.470
to defeat the stingrays.

00:02:57.470 --> 00:02:59.420
And then somebody said
to him, why don't you

00:02:59.420 --> 00:03:01.520
just file a Freedom of
Information Act request?

00:03:01.520 --> 00:03:03.920
So he filed a Freedom of
Information Act request,

00:03:03.920 --> 00:03:06.040
and he was stonewalled
for a very long time.

00:03:06.040 --> 00:03:07.420
And so he hired--

00:03:07.420 --> 00:03:09.440
or, he joined up with
this man, Matt Topic,

00:03:09.440 --> 00:03:12.050
who is a lawyer in
Chicago who litigates

00:03:12.050 --> 00:03:13.580
Freedom of Information request.

00:03:13.580 --> 00:03:16.170
In fact, Matt was involved
in the release of the Laquan

00:03:16.170 --> 00:03:18.169
McDonald video in Chicago.

00:03:18.169 --> 00:03:20.210
And what they learned was
that the Chicago police

00:03:20.210 --> 00:03:23.960
had, for many years,
been using stingrays.

00:03:23.960 --> 00:03:25.820
And when they try to
dig deeper, and ask

00:03:25.820 --> 00:03:28.340
a lot of questions about--
did you have court authority?

00:03:28.340 --> 00:03:30.194
Had you vetted the
legality of this?

00:03:30.194 --> 00:03:31.610
What were you doing
with the data?

00:03:31.610 --> 00:03:32.810
Were you storing the data?

00:03:32.810 --> 00:03:34.916
They got stonewalled again.

00:03:34.916 --> 00:03:36.290
The city of Chicago
hired a firm,

00:03:36.290 --> 00:03:38.415
and quickly spent a couple
hundred thousand dollars

00:03:38.415 --> 00:03:40.107
on not answering any
of their questions.

00:03:40.107 --> 00:03:41.690
But while that was
happening, and they

00:03:41.690 --> 00:03:43.310
were getting kind
of non-responses,

00:03:43.310 --> 00:03:45.390
people started to notice
around the country

00:03:45.390 --> 00:03:48.290
that the same non-responses,
almost in identical language,

00:03:48.290 --> 00:03:51.710
were appearing from police
departments in California

00:03:51.710 --> 00:03:52.965
and in Georgia.

00:03:52.965 --> 00:03:55.340
And eventually, people piece
together what was happening,

00:03:55.340 --> 00:03:58.040
which is that the FBI
had gotten stingrays

00:03:58.040 --> 00:04:00.800
into the hands of local
law enforcement agencies

00:04:00.800 --> 00:04:02.360
with non-disclosure
agreements that

00:04:02.360 --> 00:04:05.870
said that no matter what, they
couldn't reveal what technology

00:04:05.870 --> 00:04:06.650
was being used.

00:04:06.650 --> 00:04:08.780
So for years, law
enforcement agencies

00:04:08.780 --> 00:04:11.210
had not been getting court
orders, or lying to judges

00:04:11.210 --> 00:04:12.446
and getting court orders.

00:04:12.446 --> 00:04:13.820
There was even a
clause that said

00:04:13.820 --> 00:04:15.528
that if you were in
the middle of a trial

00:04:15.528 --> 00:04:17.779
and you were about to say
what the technology was,

00:04:17.779 --> 00:04:19.760
that you had to-- the prosecutor
had to dismiss the case.

00:04:19.760 --> 00:04:21.680
And there are instances
where that happened.

00:04:21.680 --> 00:04:24.830
And so that's one example of law
enforcement use of technology.

00:04:24.830 --> 00:04:26.512
And we'll be back to that.

00:04:26.512 --> 00:04:27.720
But here's a different story.

00:04:27.720 --> 00:04:29.330
So this is Tamir Rice.

00:04:29.330 --> 00:04:31.400
Tamir Rice, as I
think all of you know,

00:04:31.400 --> 00:04:33.770
was playing with a toy gun
in a park in Cleveland,

00:04:33.770 --> 00:04:36.020
and somebody called the
police and said that there was

00:04:36.020 --> 00:04:37.760
a male with a gun in the park.

00:04:37.760 --> 00:04:38.790
The police responded.

00:04:38.790 --> 00:04:40.580
Dispatch never relayed
the information

00:04:40.580 --> 00:04:41.480
that it might have
been a candidate,

00:04:41.480 --> 00:04:43.010
it might have been a toy gun.

00:04:43.010 --> 00:04:46.340
They came flying into
the park in a squad car--

00:04:46.340 --> 00:04:47.330
a patrol car.

00:04:47.330 --> 00:04:50.226
They stopped within
just feet of Tamir Rice.

00:04:50.226 --> 00:04:52.100
And within seconds, an
officer had jumped out

00:04:52.100 --> 00:04:54.340
and shot him twice, left
him on the ground bleeding.

00:04:54.340 --> 00:04:57.111
They didn't have any
emergency care equipment it.

00:04:57.111 --> 00:04:58.860
Took several minutes
for EMS to get there.

00:04:58.860 --> 00:05:02.030
And as you all know, he died.

00:05:02.030 --> 00:05:04.010
This is Charles and Etta Carter.

00:05:04.010 --> 00:05:07.790
So Charles and Etta Carter
lived outside of Philadelphia.

00:05:07.790 --> 00:05:09.530
Very humble jobs for many years.

00:05:09.530 --> 00:05:12.860
They had one kid who got her
PhD in developmental psychology,

00:05:12.860 --> 00:05:14.392
super proud of her.

00:05:14.392 --> 00:05:16.850
She gets a new job in Florida
working in the school system.

00:05:16.850 --> 00:05:19.340
She gets married, they buy a
new house, everything's new.

00:05:19.340 --> 00:05:21.050
So they do what good
parents do, they

00:05:21.050 --> 00:05:23.780
loaded up a van full of stuff
that the couple might need,

00:05:23.780 --> 00:05:25.310
and they went down to Florida.

00:05:25.310 --> 00:05:27.044
And they stayed for
a couple of months,

00:05:27.044 --> 00:05:28.460
and then when they
were done, they

00:05:28.460 --> 00:05:29.900
turned around and came back.

00:05:29.900 --> 00:05:32.240
And on a really,
really hot July day,

00:05:32.240 --> 00:05:35.005
they were stopped by the
Maryland State Patrol.

00:05:35.005 --> 00:05:36.380
And all the Maryland
State Patrol

00:05:36.380 --> 00:05:38.180
ever said was that
Charles had been

00:05:38.180 --> 00:05:40.910
driving wobbly, or weaving.

00:05:40.910 --> 00:05:42.430
They took them out of the car.

00:05:42.430 --> 00:05:45.380
They put them up on an
embankment out of the van.

00:05:45.380 --> 00:05:47.390
They started to take
everything out of the van.

00:05:47.390 --> 00:05:50.420
They tore open bags
of laundry detergent,

00:05:50.420 --> 00:05:52.430
breakfast cereal,
wedding invitations

00:05:52.430 --> 00:05:53.870
from her daughter's wedding.

00:05:53.870 --> 00:05:56.810
They tossed the wedding
dress out into the back.

00:05:56.810 --> 00:05:59.480
Fortunately it had been wrapped
up and wasn't destroyed.

00:05:59.480 --> 00:06:02.770
Took out lawn chairs,
took apart a refrigerator.

00:06:02.770 --> 00:06:04.550
And all the while,
the Carters sat out

00:06:04.550 --> 00:06:06.590
on this embankment in the heat.

00:06:06.590 --> 00:06:07.730
They called a drug dog in.

00:06:07.730 --> 00:06:10.730
The drug dog urinated
around their belongings.

00:06:10.730 --> 00:06:13.246
And eventually, on
several occasions,

00:06:13.246 --> 00:06:14.870
Etta Carter, who had
a bladder problem,

00:06:14.870 --> 00:06:17.453
asked if she could use a Porta
Potti that they had in the van.

00:06:17.453 --> 00:06:18.710
And the police said no.

00:06:18.710 --> 00:06:20.810
They threatened to cuff
her if she got up again.

00:06:20.810 --> 00:06:24.110
And so, on a day that
was her 40th anniversary,

00:06:24.110 --> 00:06:26.060
she was forced to
sit on an embankment,

00:06:26.060 --> 00:06:29.690
and urinated all over herself
while the officers looked

00:06:29.690 --> 00:06:31.760
through her belongings.

00:06:31.760 --> 00:06:34.850
They eventually let them
go with just a warning.

00:06:34.850 --> 00:06:37.242
Never an apology of any sort.

00:06:37.242 --> 00:06:39.200
They went to a rest stop
so she could clean up.

00:06:39.200 --> 00:06:41.330
They went back to their
home in Philadelphia.

00:06:41.330 --> 00:06:44.630
They had several sleepless
nights, didn't know what to do.

00:06:44.630 --> 00:06:46.700
Eventually went to the
AAA looking for help.

00:06:46.700 --> 00:06:50.750
The AAA sent them to
the ACLU of Maryland,

00:06:50.750 --> 00:06:52.000
and there was a lawsuit filed.

00:06:52.000 --> 00:06:52.970
It was eventually settled.

00:06:52.970 --> 00:06:54.406
But the truly
remarkable thing was

00:06:54.406 --> 00:06:56.030
that throughout the
entire litigation--

00:06:56.030 --> 00:06:57.650
I'd read through
all the depositions,

00:06:57.650 --> 00:06:58.910
nobody in the
Maryland State Patrol

00:06:58.910 --> 00:07:00.368
ever thought that
anything had gone

00:07:00.368 --> 00:07:05.330
wrong, that anything had ever
happened outside of procedure.

00:07:05.330 --> 00:07:08.750
This is a slide just to
tell a story of a fellow who

00:07:08.750 --> 00:07:12.800
was an Iraqi war vet who wakes
up in his apartment complex

00:07:12.800 --> 00:07:15.200
in the suburbs here
in the United States.

00:07:15.200 --> 00:07:17.900
And because he'd been
on many raids himself,

00:07:17.900 --> 00:07:20.540
knew exactly what was happening
when he woke up to gun barrels

00:07:20.540 --> 00:07:21.650
in his face.

00:07:21.650 --> 00:07:25.010
He just had no idea why
any of it was happening.

00:07:25.010 --> 00:07:27.864
It turned out that his
apartment was being--

00:07:27.864 --> 00:07:29.030
undergoing some maintenance.

00:07:29.030 --> 00:07:30.640
And so the department
development

00:07:30.640 --> 00:07:31.970
had moved him into a
different department.

00:07:31.970 --> 00:07:34.460
Some of the neighbors wondered
who was in that apartment.

00:07:34.460 --> 00:07:36.043
They called the
police, and the police

00:07:36.043 --> 00:07:37.572
responded with a SWAT raid.

00:07:37.572 --> 00:07:39.530
He went down to the police
station the next day

00:07:39.530 --> 00:07:43.830
and said, investigate,
call the apartment complex,

00:07:43.830 --> 00:07:46.170
ask security who was
in that apartment.

00:07:46.170 --> 00:07:47.992
And they said, we
don't investigate.

00:07:47.992 --> 00:07:50.325
It kind of gets in the way
of our apprehending suspects.

00:07:52.900 --> 00:07:55.115
This is just-- there are--

00:07:55.115 --> 00:07:56.609
you're driving
under the influence,

00:07:56.609 --> 00:07:58.150
cops want to give
you a breathalyzer.

00:07:58.150 --> 00:08:00.108
But if it's drugs, the
breathalyzer won't work,

00:08:00.108 --> 00:08:02.710
so it's become-- in fact, it's
becoming increasingly common.

00:08:02.710 --> 00:08:05.620
I now get calls about this all
the time for-- particularly

00:08:05.620 --> 00:08:08.680
in the Midwest, for police to
take folks to the hospital,

00:08:08.680 --> 00:08:11.800
and have them forcibly
catheterized to get a urine

00:08:11.800 --> 00:08:12.730
sample.

00:08:12.730 --> 00:08:15.730
And including a case
where a fellow who

00:08:15.730 --> 00:08:18.040
refused to sit still
for the catheter

00:08:18.040 --> 00:08:21.220
was strapped to a gurney so that
they could insert the catheter.

00:08:21.220 --> 00:08:23.609
And then just a quick reminder
that the NSA, as we all

00:08:23.609 --> 00:08:25.900
learned from Edward Snowden,
was gathering the metadata

00:08:25.900 --> 00:08:29.230
from all of our
telephone communications,

00:08:29.230 --> 00:08:31.250
and also some of our
internet connections.

00:08:31.250 --> 00:08:34.929
So the question I have that
I ask folks all the time is,

00:08:34.929 --> 00:08:36.820
what do all these
seemingly different stories

00:08:36.820 --> 00:08:37.720
have in common?

00:08:37.720 --> 00:08:40.807
And we don't tend to think
of them as the same story

00:08:40.807 --> 00:08:41.890
here in the United States.

00:08:41.890 --> 00:08:44.740
We think about racial profiling,
we think about militarization,

00:08:44.740 --> 00:08:48.520
we think about technology,
we think about use of force.

00:08:48.520 --> 00:08:50.480
But my argument in the
book and in the work

00:08:50.480 --> 00:08:52.480
I do with the policing
project that I've started

00:08:52.480 --> 00:08:56.620
is that all of these stories
are united by a governance

00:08:56.620 --> 00:08:59.380
failure, which requires
me to teach you

00:08:59.380 --> 00:09:02.390
all of a minute of
constitutional law.

00:09:02.390 --> 00:09:04.060
So when we think
about government

00:09:04.060 --> 00:09:05.560
in the United States,
we think about

00:09:05.560 --> 00:09:07.100
democratic accountability.

00:09:07.100 --> 00:09:10.270
And I divide that up into
front end and back end

00:09:10.270 --> 00:09:11.102
accountability.

00:09:11.102 --> 00:09:13.060
And we know all about
front end accountability.

00:09:13.060 --> 00:09:15.185
It's what you think of when
you think of democracy.

00:09:15.185 --> 00:09:17.440
It's the idea that
we have rules,

00:09:17.440 --> 00:09:20.200
that we put the rules in place
before officials act so we

00:09:20.200 --> 00:09:21.617
know what they're going to do.

00:09:21.617 --> 00:09:22.450
They're transparent.

00:09:22.450 --> 00:09:23.920
We know what the rules are.

00:09:23.920 --> 00:09:26.370
Indeed, we have a voice
in what those rules are.

00:09:26.370 --> 00:09:28.704
There's always some
form of public input.

00:09:28.704 --> 00:09:31.120
We try when we can to make
sure that the benefits outweigh

00:09:31.120 --> 00:09:32.290
the costs.

00:09:32.290 --> 00:09:34.210
Now we have back end
accountability, too,

00:09:34.210 --> 00:09:37.505
which is to say, what
keeps that system running

00:09:37.505 --> 00:09:39.880
and keeps it honest is that
we have courts that make sure

00:09:39.880 --> 00:09:42.694
that everything that's supposed
to happen up front happens.

00:09:42.694 --> 00:09:44.110
But it's the up
front part that we

00:09:44.110 --> 00:09:47.050
think of as democratic
accountability,

00:09:47.050 --> 00:09:48.630
but not in policing.

00:09:48.630 --> 00:09:51.310
In policing, for bizarre
historical reasons,

00:09:51.310 --> 00:09:53.529
we have almost no front
end accountability.

00:09:53.529 --> 00:09:55.570
And all of our accountability
is on the back end.

00:09:55.570 --> 00:09:58.150
It's things like inspectors
general, and civilian review

00:09:58.150 --> 00:10:01.360
boards, and
court-appointed monitors,

00:10:01.360 --> 00:10:03.772
and body cameras-- the sort
of stuff Deborah deals with,

00:10:03.772 --> 00:10:05.230
and she'll talk a
little bit about.

00:10:05.230 --> 00:10:07.040
Even body cameras, if you
stop and think about them,

00:10:07.040 --> 00:10:08.290
are back end accountability.

00:10:08.290 --> 00:10:10.947
All the stuff on the
back end is designed

00:10:10.947 --> 00:10:13.030
to kick in when something
bad has happened to say,

00:10:13.030 --> 00:10:14.863
can we figure out, was
somebody responsible?

00:10:14.863 --> 00:10:16.120
Did something go wrong?

00:10:16.120 --> 00:10:17.680
Is somebody to blame?

00:10:17.680 --> 00:10:19.300
But what we don't
do around policing,

00:10:19.300 --> 00:10:22.357
and this is the key thing that
I think has gone wrong is,

00:10:22.357 --> 00:10:24.190
we don't involve the
public on the front end

00:10:24.190 --> 00:10:26.920
to say, how do we
want to be policed?

00:10:26.920 --> 00:10:29.260
What should the rules be
by which we're policed?

00:10:29.260 --> 00:10:31.810
Should we all know what those
rules are, and have input

00:10:31.810 --> 00:10:33.650
into them?

00:10:33.650 --> 00:10:35.080
And the interesting
thing is, when

00:10:35.080 --> 00:10:37.450
we do have that input
here in the United States,

00:10:37.450 --> 00:10:38.890
when something
happens to cause us

00:10:38.890 --> 00:10:42.280
to have that input for people
to get annoyed and speak up,

00:10:42.280 --> 00:10:44.410
policy changes,
policing changes.

00:10:44.410 --> 00:10:46.580
So I'm sure you
recognize this picture.

00:10:46.580 --> 00:10:48.400
It's one of the
images from Ferguson.

00:10:48.400 --> 00:10:51.280
After Ferguson, there's a big
debate about militarization.

00:10:51.280 --> 00:10:52.960
That debate goes on
around the country.

00:10:52.960 --> 00:10:57.820
And as befits a federal
system and a democracy,

00:10:57.820 --> 00:11:00.759
different governments, different
states at the local level all

00:11:00.759 --> 00:11:02.800
adopt different policies
about what should happen

00:11:02.800 --> 00:11:04.120
with the military equipment.

00:11:04.120 --> 00:11:06.190
Some decide to keep
it, some decide

00:11:06.190 --> 00:11:09.040
to ship it back, some decide
that it's got to be online,

00:11:09.040 --> 00:11:12.100
what equipment the government
has, so that folks can respond.

00:11:12.100 --> 00:11:14.620
Some decide that the government
actually-- the police

00:11:14.620 --> 00:11:16.540
have to come to the
city council, whatever,

00:11:16.540 --> 00:11:18.010
and ask to get the permission.

00:11:18.010 --> 00:11:20.150
But the policy changes.

00:11:20.150 --> 00:11:21.910
Similarly with drones--
a lot of states

00:11:21.910 --> 00:11:23.595
are now adopting
drone legislation

00:11:23.595 --> 00:11:25.720
because people are focused
on the use of technology

00:11:25.720 --> 00:11:26.980
around policing.

00:11:26.980 --> 00:11:29.320
And even after the
Snowden revelations,

00:11:29.320 --> 00:11:31.324
though it took Congress
a long period of time,

00:11:31.324 --> 00:11:32.740
eventually what
happened is, there

00:11:32.740 --> 00:11:33.820
was a big debate in Congress.

00:11:33.820 --> 00:11:35.236
And we decided
that the government

00:11:35.236 --> 00:11:36.520
shouldn't hold all that data.

00:11:36.520 --> 00:11:38.890
And instead, it should be
held by private companies,

00:11:38.890 --> 00:11:41.060
and should only be
available under court order.

00:11:41.060 --> 00:11:42.820
So when we get the
public involved

00:11:42.820 --> 00:11:45.340
in the front end, which
we don't do very often,

00:11:45.340 --> 00:11:48.300
policing changes.

00:11:48.300 --> 00:11:50.220
And the last kind
of big point I want

00:11:50.220 --> 00:11:53.392
to make with some more images
is that this, ironically,

00:11:53.392 --> 00:11:54.350
is good for the police.

00:11:54.350 --> 00:11:57.010
So this is the sell to the
police, but it's important.

00:11:57.010 --> 00:12:00.060
So there's been a lot of talk
about legitimacy of policing,

00:12:00.060 --> 00:12:02.150
about trust in
policing agencies.

00:12:02.150 --> 00:12:03.900
Well, it's not that
surprising that people

00:12:03.900 --> 00:12:06.210
don't trust that there are
legitimacy issues when people

00:12:06.210 --> 00:12:07.668
aren't engaged,
and when they don't

00:12:07.668 --> 00:12:09.700
have a voice in what happens.

00:12:09.700 --> 00:12:12.210
And so when there are
things like Stop and Frisk,

00:12:12.210 --> 00:12:15.090
hundreds of thousands of
people a year in New York.

00:12:15.090 --> 00:12:17.070
Or when there's
surveillance going

00:12:17.070 --> 00:12:19.020
on that people don't
know about, then

00:12:19.020 --> 00:12:21.930
in fact, when people learn,
or when people observe that,

00:12:21.930 --> 00:12:24.752
there is a huge loss of
legitimacy and trust.

00:12:24.752 --> 00:12:26.460
And that's painful
for policing agencies,

00:12:26.460 --> 00:12:28.320
which need to understand--
and what progressive chiefs

00:12:28.320 --> 00:12:30.451
understand is-- in fact,
we were working in Camden,

00:12:30.451 --> 00:12:32.700
and there was a horrible
incident of an eight-year-old

00:12:32.700 --> 00:12:36.300
girl that was shot and killed
in crossfire from a gang fight.

00:12:36.300 --> 00:12:40.460
And somebody came forward,
a very wealthy person

00:12:40.460 --> 00:12:42.770
elsewhere in New Jersey,
and offered up a big reward.

00:12:42.770 --> 00:12:45.390
And nobody took the money
because what happens

00:12:45.390 --> 00:12:47.984
is that, in these neighborhoods
when something goes wrong

00:12:47.984 --> 00:12:50.400
and there's a shooting, nobody
cooperates with the police.

00:12:50.400 --> 00:12:51.690
Nobody wants to
speak to the police.

00:12:51.690 --> 00:12:54.231
People are threatened, they're
afraid to speak to the police.

00:12:54.231 --> 00:12:56.040
And it's that lack of
legitimacy and trust

00:12:56.040 --> 00:12:59.082
that keeps us from getting that
engagement with the public.

00:12:59.082 --> 00:13:00.540
But here's kind of
an ironic story.

00:13:00.540 --> 00:13:05.100
So Compton, part of
the sprawling place

00:13:05.100 --> 00:13:08.329
that is Los Angeles, the
police department decides--

00:13:08.329 --> 00:13:09.870
the L.A. sheriff's
department decides

00:13:09.870 --> 00:13:12.328
that they're going to try out
some surveillance technology.

00:13:12.328 --> 00:13:16.410
Big airplane in the sky,
remarkable resolution,

00:13:16.410 --> 00:13:17.700
track crime that way.

00:13:17.700 --> 00:13:19.350
Eventually, people find out.

00:13:19.350 --> 00:13:20.310
It's in the newspapers.

00:13:20.310 --> 00:13:22.210
People are extremely angry.

00:13:22.210 --> 00:13:24.150
Remarkable statement by
the public information

00:13:24.150 --> 00:13:25.858
officer for the L.A.
sheriff's department

00:13:25.858 --> 00:13:27.510
says, look, when we
did this, we knew

00:13:27.510 --> 00:13:29.550
that people kind of get
nervous about Big Brother, eye

00:13:29.550 --> 00:13:30.060
in the sky.

00:13:30.060 --> 00:13:31.560
So we thought we
just better kind of

00:13:31.560 --> 00:13:33.197
keep it hush-hush
and not tell anybody.

00:13:33.197 --> 00:13:35.280
Obviously people were
unhappy when they found out,

00:13:35.280 --> 00:13:36.090
and that was the end of it.

00:13:36.090 --> 00:13:37.500
But down the street
in Lancaster,

00:13:37.500 --> 00:13:41.447
exact same technology, public
debate, they decided to use it.

00:13:41.447 --> 00:13:42.780
And that happens time and again.

00:13:42.780 --> 00:13:43.863
It's happened with drones.

00:13:43.863 --> 00:13:45.290
It happened here in Seattle.

00:13:45.290 --> 00:13:47.281
The police department
got some drones,

00:13:47.281 --> 00:13:49.280
people learned about it,
were extremely unhappy.

00:13:49.280 --> 00:13:50.946
They eventually had
to ship them to L.A.

00:13:50.946 --> 00:13:52.900
Just a quiet the tempest.

00:13:52.900 --> 00:13:56.070
So the idea I want
to leave you with

00:13:56.070 --> 00:13:58.467
is that bringing front end
accountability to policing

00:13:58.467 --> 00:14:00.300
is really important,
and makes a difference.

00:14:00.300 --> 00:14:02.850
I started an organization called
The Policing Project to work

00:14:02.850 --> 00:14:05.290
on those kinds of issues.

00:14:05.290 --> 00:14:07.050
We do lots of different
things, but I just

00:14:07.050 --> 00:14:08.675
want to mention a
couple that I thought

00:14:08.675 --> 00:14:10.990
would be of particular
interest in this room.

00:14:10.990 --> 00:14:12.960
So one thing that
we're doing is,

00:14:12.960 --> 00:14:15.284
we're working all over the
country bringing community

00:14:15.284 --> 00:14:17.700
voice to policing, trying out
different models of bringing

00:14:17.700 --> 00:14:19.366
the police and the
communities together.

00:14:19.366 --> 00:14:22.350
Decide how they
want to be policed,

00:14:22.350 --> 00:14:24.630
often working with,
as you might guess,

00:14:24.630 --> 00:14:26.310
extremely marginalized
neighborhoods,

00:14:26.310 --> 00:14:27.575
communities of color.

00:14:27.575 --> 00:14:28.950
The other thing
that we're doing,

00:14:28.950 --> 00:14:30.600
which astonished
me when I started

00:14:30.600 --> 00:14:33.570
to write the book-- so you
know, I didn't believe then,

00:14:33.570 --> 00:14:35.100
and I very much
don't believe now

00:14:35.100 --> 00:14:37.170
that we're safer because
of all this policing.

00:14:37.170 --> 00:14:40.380
And I'm very curious about the
efficacy of policing practices,

00:14:40.380 --> 00:14:41.880
so I said to my
research assistants,

00:14:41.880 --> 00:14:43.296
go forth and get
me the literature

00:14:43.296 --> 00:14:45.127
on cost-benefit
analysis of policing.

00:14:45.127 --> 00:14:46.710
And they came back
with not very much.

00:14:46.710 --> 00:14:48.590
And I said, no,
seriously, there must be.

00:14:48.590 --> 00:14:50.830
We spend $100 billion a
year on public safety,

00:14:50.830 --> 00:14:52.680
there must be studies.

00:14:52.680 --> 00:14:56.236
Shockingly little cost-benefit
analysis done around policing.

00:14:56.236 --> 00:14:58.110
But the one extraordinary
fact that I learned

00:14:58.110 --> 00:15:01.860
was, in all of the little,
skimpy literature there was,

00:15:01.860 --> 00:15:05.620
no attention paid whatsoever to
the social costs of policing.

00:15:05.620 --> 00:15:08.162
So we might ask, look, we can
hire this many more officers,

00:15:08.162 --> 00:15:09.870
we can do this many
more Stop and Frisks,

00:15:09.870 --> 00:15:11.200
doesn't make us safer.

00:15:11.200 --> 00:15:13.310
We have some estimates
to the cost of crime,

00:15:13.310 --> 00:15:15.360
but no one ever
asks the question,

00:15:15.360 --> 00:15:16.980
how do we monetize
the Stop and Frisk?

00:15:16.980 --> 00:15:18.210
What is it-- what does it cost--

00:15:18.210 --> 00:15:19.900
what's the value on being
stopped and frisked?

00:15:19.900 --> 00:15:21.400
Or what's the value
on community trust

00:15:21.400 --> 00:15:22.691
if it's lost when that happens?

00:15:22.691 --> 00:15:26.370
And so around street policing
issues, around technology--

00:15:26.370 --> 00:15:29.100
which is one of the really huge
issues around policing right

00:15:29.100 --> 00:15:30.600
now, is the growth
of technology,

00:15:30.600 --> 00:15:32.790
these are the kinds of
questions we need to answer.

00:15:32.790 --> 00:15:34.050
That's all from me.

00:15:34.050 --> 00:15:36.716
My friend Deborah's now going to
talk to you a little about what

00:15:36.716 --> 00:15:38.070
she does here in Seattle.

00:15:38.070 --> 00:15:39.095
DEBORAH JACOBS:
Thank you, Barry.

00:15:39.095 --> 00:15:39.560
[APPLAUSE]

00:15:39.560 --> 00:15:40.643
BARRY FRIEDMAN: Thank you.

00:15:42.820 --> 00:15:45.130
DEBORAH JACOBS: Thank you so
much to Ana and [? Yves ?]

00:15:45.130 --> 00:15:47.170
and David for hosting us.

00:15:47.170 --> 00:15:51.470
It's really exciting to be
here, and see how you all live.

00:15:51.470 --> 00:15:55.210
So I-- after working more
than 20 years for the ACLU,

00:15:55.210 --> 00:16:00.250
I decided to settle into work,
specifically digging deep

00:16:00.250 --> 00:16:01.810
on police practices.

00:16:01.810 --> 00:16:04.780
And the reason I kind of
went to single-issue work

00:16:04.780 --> 00:16:07.450
is, I see that as the
most critical area

00:16:07.450 --> 00:16:08.470
of civil liberties.

00:16:08.470 --> 00:16:11.410
It's the most direct, immediate,
dangerous confrontation

00:16:11.410 --> 00:16:13.560
between a government
and its citizens.

00:16:13.560 --> 00:16:16.360
And it's also the gateway
to mass incarceration.

00:16:16.360 --> 00:16:18.460
And for me, for those
reasons, it really

00:16:18.460 --> 00:16:21.700
rose up as someplace where
I'd like to dedicate my time.

00:16:21.700 --> 00:16:26.320
So there aren't a ton of systems
to hold police accountable.

00:16:26.320 --> 00:16:28.060
During the Obama
administration, we've

00:16:28.060 --> 00:16:31.510
seen unprecedented
engagement with the DOJ.

00:16:31.510 --> 00:16:34.870
I think he sent the DOJ out
more on police practices issues

00:16:34.870 --> 00:16:38.980
than probably the last five
or six presidencies combined.

00:16:38.980 --> 00:16:40.940
Those kind of-- it's
really a new thing.

00:16:40.940 --> 00:16:43.560
But as we know, the
administration has changed.

00:16:43.560 --> 00:16:46.540
And I think we have lots of
evidence to see the rollback.

00:16:46.540 --> 00:16:48.610
So what's left for
accountability?

00:16:48.610 --> 00:16:50.260
And you could also
really question

00:16:50.260 --> 00:16:53.560
how the efficacy of DOJ
intervention, some success

00:16:53.560 --> 00:16:54.700
stories, some rollbacks.

00:16:54.700 --> 00:16:58.570
We'll see what happens in
Seattle, in particular.

00:16:58.570 --> 00:17:00.880
But civilian oversight
is another way

00:17:00.880 --> 00:17:02.410
of holding police accountable.

00:17:02.410 --> 00:17:06.700
My office is one of 150
offices around the country that

00:17:06.700 --> 00:17:09.880
engage in civilian-led
oversight efforts.

00:17:09.880 --> 00:17:12.369
And by the way, I'm not in
love with saying civilian

00:17:12.369 --> 00:17:14.890
because what's-- it's
versus military, right?

00:17:14.890 --> 00:17:17.500
And I don't particularly want
our police to be militarized.

00:17:17.500 --> 00:17:20.470
I also don't want to
use citizen because that

00:17:20.470 --> 00:17:23.829
excludes a big chunk of our
population unintentionally,

00:17:23.829 --> 00:17:25.000
I think.

00:17:25.000 --> 00:17:27.069
But for now, it's
civilian oversight.

00:17:27.069 --> 00:17:28.600
No two offices are the same.

00:17:28.600 --> 00:17:30.940
You can't do apples
to apples comparisons.

00:17:30.940 --> 00:17:34.810
And there's no one best
model, one best practice,

00:17:34.810 --> 00:17:36.730
or way of doing the oversight.

00:17:36.730 --> 00:17:39.940
What my office does is sort
of three key functions.

00:17:39.940 --> 00:17:42.580
When the-- so one thing is,
we oversee the King County

00:17:42.580 --> 00:17:43.840
sheriff's office.

00:17:43.840 --> 00:17:46.780
That office covers all of
unincorporated King County,

00:17:46.780 --> 00:17:50.630
and about a dozen jurisdictions
that contract for its services.

00:17:50.630 --> 00:17:56.200
So that's Burine, Shoreline,
Beaux Arts, Maple Valley,

00:17:56.200 --> 00:18:00.910
Woodinville, Muckleshoot
Reservation, and a bunch more

00:18:00.910 --> 00:18:03.290
I can't pull off
the top of my head.

00:18:03.290 --> 00:18:06.550
And so when you're in Burine,
you might see Burine police,

00:18:06.550 --> 00:18:09.199
and then you'll see a little
King County sheriff under that.

00:18:09.199 --> 00:18:10.990
So we have, compared
to the Seattle police,

00:18:10.990 --> 00:18:14.560
a really diverse geographic
and otherwise area.

00:18:14.560 --> 00:18:17.030
So you can't even compare
how Seattle does things

00:18:17.030 --> 00:18:19.510
to how King County does things.

00:18:19.510 --> 00:18:21.130
And that's something
to be mindful of.

00:18:21.130 --> 00:18:22.990
So what the activities
my office do are,

00:18:22.990 --> 00:18:25.330
one, when the sheriff's
office completes

00:18:25.330 --> 00:18:27.520
an internal investigation,
we look at it

00:18:27.520 --> 00:18:29.830
to see if it was
thorough and objective.

00:18:29.830 --> 00:18:31.600
Is there bias in
the investigation?

00:18:31.600 --> 00:18:33.740
Have they crossed their
T's and dotted their I's?

00:18:33.740 --> 00:18:37.070
Two, we do systemic reviews,
use of force trends,

00:18:37.070 --> 00:18:37.794
training issues.

00:18:37.794 --> 00:18:40.210
One of the things that drives
me crazy about the training,

00:18:40.210 --> 00:18:42.670
there's statewide, there's
a 24 hour annual training

00:18:42.670 --> 00:18:43.590
requirement.

00:18:43.590 --> 00:18:45.190
And at least the
King County sheriff's

00:18:45.190 --> 00:18:46.990
office, that's all
done electronically.

00:18:46.990 --> 00:18:49.465
None of it has to be
in-person training.

00:18:49.465 --> 00:18:52.540
And I think there are huge
costs and issues around that.

00:18:52.540 --> 00:18:54.140
Three, we do community outreach.

00:18:54.140 --> 00:18:56.279
That's me right here,
right now, talking to you.

00:18:56.279 --> 00:18:57.820
And for those of
you who think you're

00:18:57.820 --> 00:19:00.421
covered by an area of the
King County sheriff's office,

00:19:00.421 --> 00:19:01.420
I'd love to talk to you.

00:19:01.420 --> 00:19:04.660
Because we have opportunities to
engage you, and I need to help,

00:19:04.660 --> 00:19:05.200
people.

00:19:05.200 --> 00:19:07.120
So identify yourself.

00:19:07.120 --> 00:19:09.130
And then right now, we--

00:19:09.130 --> 00:19:12.310
in November, 2015, the
voters of King County

00:19:12.310 --> 00:19:15.160
voted to expand the authorities
of my office to include

00:19:15.160 --> 00:19:16.960
individual investigations.

00:19:16.960 --> 00:19:20.200
The King County council has just
passed an ordinance to do that.

00:19:20.200 --> 00:19:21.730
And now that
ordinance is subject

00:19:21.730 --> 00:19:24.610
to collective bargaining with
the 11 different unions that

00:19:24.610 --> 00:19:27.640
represent the law enforcement
that make up the King County

00:19:27.640 --> 00:19:28.690
sheriff's office.

00:19:28.690 --> 00:19:30.730
So this will be a new
experience for me to see,

00:19:30.730 --> 00:19:33.599
can we hold onto these
voter-endorsed rights?

00:19:33.599 --> 00:19:35.890
It might interest you to know
that in Washington State,

00:19:35.890 --> 00:19:37.840
a collective bargaining
agreement has

00:19:37.840 --> 00:19:41.410
a higher legal authority
than an ordinance,

00:19:41.410 --> 00:19:44.400
or even a vote of the people.

00:19:44.400 --> 00:19:49.120
So I'm trying to live out some
of what Barry's talking about.

00:19:49.120 --> 00:19:50.980
And he's correct in
saying a lot of what we

00:19:50.980 --> 00:19:53.140
do are the back end solutions.

00:19:53.140 --> 00:19:54.970
What can come on the front end?

00:19:54.970 --> 00:19:56.710
So in our new
ordinance, one piece

00:19:56.710 --> 00:20:00.370
is to have input on policies
before they're adopted.

00:20:00.370 --> 00:20:02.980
Non-binding input, but
input nevertheless.

00:20:02.980 --> 00:20:05.380
And that, as it happens, was
the piece of the ordinance

00:20:05.380 --> 00:20:07.000
that they fought
hardest against.

00:20:07.000 --> 00:20:07.870
And I don't--

00:20:07.870 --> 00:20:09.490
I'm not sure what
that means, Barry.

00:20:09.490 --> 00:20:11.710
You know, how much
is that related

00:20:11.710 --> 00:20:16.450
to defensiveness of like,
no, we decide how we do it?

00:20:16.450 --> 00:20:18.600
But the future is
what Barry describes.

00:20:18.600 --> 00:20:20.860
It's-- when people talk
about community policing,

00:20:20.860 --> 00:20:23.350
most of us get on our head,
that's a cop out of his car

00:20:23.350 --> 00:20:25.480
in the community
to talk to people.

00:20:25.480 --> 00:20:28.870
I think we need to take a more
aspirational viewpoint, which

00:20:28.870 --> 00:20:32.410
is that community policing
is about the community,

00:20:32.410 --> 00:20:35.650
through democratic processes,
setting the priorities of what

00:20:35.650 --> 00:20:36.910
the police should be doing.

00:20:36.910 --> 00:20:38.650
And Seattle has great
precedent for this.

00:20:38.650 --> 00:20:41.060
When we-- God, how
long ago, 20 years ago,

00:20:41.060 --> 00:20:43.750
passed a law that said marijuana
should be the lowest law

00:20:43.750 --> 00:20:45.350
enforcement priority.

00:20:45.350 --> 00:20:48.070
I don't think that's been done
here, or anywhere else since.

00:20:48.070 --> 00:20:49.300
But it's the idea.

00:20:49.300 --> 00:20:52.327
It's like, well, what do we
care most about in our community

00:20:52.327 --> 00:20:53.410
that we want police to do?

00:20:53.410 --> 00:20:55.360
And what we don't want them
to do, how are we going

00:20:55.360 --> 00:20:56.620
to make up that difference?

00:20:56.620 --> 00:20:59.950
So technology, I just want
to say a couple of things,

00:20:59.950 --> 00:21:02.930
and then I'll not take
up any more of the time.

00:21:02.930 --> 00:21:04.930
I know you want to ask
Barry a lot of questions.

00:21:04.930 --> 00:21:07.840
But one thing that's a
big issue with police

00:21:07.840 --> 00:21:11.680
is adopting technologies without
having thoughtful processes

00:21:11.680 --> 00:21:13.810
for the policies behind them.

00:21:13.810 --> 00:21:16.060
So I just found out that
King County sheriff's

00:21:16.060 --> 00:21:17.950
has been using a
technology that there

00:21:17.950 --> 00:21:22.120
was no real analysis of like,
what are the privacy rights?

00:21:22.120 --> 00:21:24.380
How is this going to
be properly stored?

00:21:24.380 --> 00:21:25.870
Or-- all those issues.

00:21:25.870 --> 00:21:28.690
So I think for those of
you in the tech community,

00:21:28.690 --> 00:21:31.854
if you're interested in policy
around privacy and technology,

00:21:31.854 --> 00:21:32.770
there's a lot of room.

00:21:32.770 --> 00:21:35.103
And I personally would love
to have your help, if that's

00:21:35.103 --> 00:21:37.720
something, you're engaged with.

00:21:37.720 --> 00:21:40.991
Another issue is better
technologies for police.

00:21:40.991 --> 00:21:42.490
So one thing I said
at lunch, if you

00:21:42.490 --> 00:21:44.530
want to become a
billionaire is, come up

00:21:44.530 --> 00:21:47.680
with a great, non-lethal
way to stop people.

00:21:47.680 --> 00:21:50.830
Tasers are sometimes
non-lethal, but if you

00:21:50.830 --> 00:21:52.670
have an underlying
medical condition,

00:21:52.670 --> 00:21:56.530
many hundreds of people now have
died from Taser applications.

00:21:56.530 --> 00:21:58.600
And that's what they
rely on now, it's Tasers.

00:21:58.600 --> 00:22:01.030
You have a gun on one
hip, a Taser on the other.

00:22:01.030 --> 00:22:02.840
And unless they're
coming up fast at you,

00:22:02.840 --> 00:22:04.760
you're going to take your
Taser and give it a try.

00:22:04.760 --> 00:22:07.093
But it's not always reliable,
and they don't necessarily

00:22:07.093 --> 00:22:08.470
trust it.

00:22:08.470 --> 00:22:12.370
So they are, by the way--
they've already experimented

00:22:12.370 --> 00:22:15.160
with web--

00:22:15.160 --> 00:22:16.730
a net you can shoot.

00:22:16.730 --> 00:22:20.520
But the newest trend is
sticky gum that you shoot.

00:22:20.520 --> 00:22:22.150
And people-- it's
like a cartoon.

00:22:22.150 --> 00:22:24.790
And go on YouTube, and look
for the demonstrations.

00:22:24.790 --> 00:22:27.760
But they kind of stop people
from being able to move.

00:22:27.760 --> 00:22:28.960
Those are not in use yet.

00:22:28.960 --> 00:22:30.320
There's a lot of room for that.

00:22:30.320 --> 00:22:31.820
And I think it's necessary.

00:22:31.820 --> 00:22:34.330
And then finally,
one thing I notice

00:22:34.330 --> 00:22:37.570
is that underlying systems
with which policing is managed

00:22:37.570 --> 00:22:40.940
leave a lot of room
for improvement.

00:22:40.940 --> 00:22:43.300
There's an industry
standard called IAPro--

00:22:43.300 --> 00:22:46.570
Internal Affairs Pro, where all
the data is kept in most police

00:22:46.570 --> 00:22:47.500
departments.

00:22:47.500 --> 00:22:50.020
And there's so many
shortcomings to those programs.

00:22:50.020 --> 00:22:53.500
And so this is an area where I
think there is tremendous need.

00:22:53.500 --> 00:22:56.470
Again, I'm not a
big body camera fan.

00:22:56.470 --> 00:22:58.510
I'm not against
technologies inherently.

00:22:58.510 --> 00:23:00.580
I think they need to
work for the people.

00:23:00.580 --> 00:23:02.520
Problem with body cams,
among other things,

00:23:02.520 --> 00:23:04.810
is, they only face one way.

00:23:04.810 --> 00:23:07.060
And I think where you have
something like a dash cam

00:23:07.060 --> 00:23:08.890
where you're performing
in front of it--

00:23:08.890 --> 00:23:10.810
although they can
also avoid those.

00:23:10.810 --> 00:23:11.920
So a lot of issues there.

00:23:11.920 --> 00:23:14.440
And I really appreciate
your interest in this.

00:23:14.440 --> 00:23:17.050
My office is one of only
two independent oversight

00:23:17.050 --> 00:23:18.340
offices in the state.

00:23:18.340 --> 00:23:19.857
The other one's in Spokane.

00:23:19.857 --> 00:23:21.940
I'd love for you to take
an interest in what we're

00:23:21.940 --> 00:23:24.040
trying to do because it's
really about the future.

00:23:24.040 --> 00:23:26.740
What kind of accountability
can we as citizens

00:23:26.740 --> 00:23:28.420
assert in these dynamics?

00:23:28.420 --> 00:23:30.880
And it's a work in progress
trying to get it right,

00:23:30.880 --> 00:23:32.230
and lots of challenges.

00:23:32.230 --> 00:23:35.050
But I can't think of a more
important field in which you

00:23:35.050 --> 00:23:36.790
could share your talents.

00:23:36.790 --> 00:23:37.810
So thank you.

