question for both of you,

00:25:15.890 --> 00:25:18.680
and for King County,
what's stopping us

00:25:18.680 --> 00:25:21.980
right now from just rolling
out a larger community policing

00:25:21.980 --> 00:25:22.790
effort?

00:25:22.790 --> 00:25:25.220
BARRY FRIEDMAN: So
first, I just want

00:25:25.220 --> 00:25:27.170
to draw a distinction,
which Deborah drew,

00:25:27.170 --> 00:25:29.420
between community policing
and community engagement

00:25:29.420 --> 00:25:30.711
because I think it's important.

00:25:30.711 --> 00:25:32.459
So community policing,
as you identified,

00:25:32.459 --> 00:25:34.250
is a way to get the
cops out of their cars,

00:25:34.250 --> 00:25:36.583
and walking around, and meeting
people in the community.

00:25:36.583 --> 00:25:40.340
And generally, we should favor
that as a method of policing.

00:25:40.340 --> 00:25:43.089
Though we should
also be conscious

00:25:43.089 --> 00:25:45.380
of unintended consequences,
because we always have them

00:25:45.380 --> 00:25:46.070
around policing.

00:25:46.070 --> 00:25:48.257
And so there was
some community that

00:25:48.257 --> 00:25:50.840
had this idea that it would be
great if, on Friday afternoons,

00:25:50.840 --> 00:25:53.381
the cops would just come up and
high-five all the kids coming

00:25:53.381 --> 00:25:54.250
out of school.

00:25:54.250 --> 00:25:55.700
A lot of parents
were like, whoa,

00:25:55.700 --> 00:25:57.140
we just don't
really want the cops

00:25:57.140 --> 00:25:59.000
around high-fiving anybody.

00:25:59.000 --> 00:26:01.280
And you know, that's a
function of a loss of trust,

00:26:01.280 --> 00:26:03.521
and a loss of legitimacy.

00:26:03.521 --> 00:26:05.270
We were moving toward
a community policing

00:26:05.270 --> 00:26:09.080
model in this country, and
then we had a war on drugs.

00:26:09.080 --> 00:26:10.750
And then we had a war on terror.

00:26:10.750 --> 00:26:14.120
And it's hard to have community
policing when you're at war.

00:26:14.120 --> 00:26:17.780
And so Sue Rahr, who is the
former Sheriff of King County

00:26:17.780 --> 00:26:19.670
and now runs a training
facility talks a lot

00:26:19.670 --> 00:26:21.380
about the difference
between cops

00:26:21.380 --> 00:26:23.900
being warriors and guardians.

00:26:23.900 --> 00:26:26.720
But a lot of departments
are moving toward community

00:26:26.720 --> 00:26:27.470
policing models.

00:26:27.470 --> 00:26:30.320
The NYPD is moving pretty
quickly toward one.

00:26:30.320 --> 00:26:32.540
We're doing some
work in Chicago,

00:26:32.540 --> 00:26:34.040
and they're trying
to move themself

00:26:34.040 --> 00:26:35.789
to set up that kind
of community policing.

00:26:35.789 --> 00:26:38.097
So it's the right direction.

00:26:38.097 --> 00:26:39.680
DEBORAH JACOBS: I
would just throw in,

00:26:39.680 --> 00:26:41.860
one other thing is resource.

00:26:41.860 --> 00:26:45.660
You ask what stops
it, is resources.

00:26:45.660 --> 00:26:48.470
There are so many
differences in capacities

00:26:48.470 --> 00:26:49.530
of police departments.

00:26:49.530 --> 00:26:50.780
And you know, how many people?

00:26:50.780 --> 00:26:52.279
Are they doing--
King County happens

00:26:52.279 --> 00:26:53.870
to be an extremely
lean department.

00:26:53.870 --> 00:26:56.480
That will give you an example
to compare it to Seattle.

00:26:56.480 --> 00:26:59.690
In Seattle, they've done
amazing work on their crisis

00:26:59.690 --> 00:27:03.630
intervention in terms of
people in behavioral crisis.

00:27:03.630 --> 00:27:05.870
So if they get a call, for
example, with a suicidal,

00:27:05.870 --> 00:27:09.159
possibly armed person,
they'll spend up to an hour--

00:27:09.159 --> 00:27:11.450
first of all, they'll have
an officer there that's been

00:27:11.450 --> 00:27:14.690
trained and certified in--

00:27:14.690 --> 00:27:17.780
they call it CIT, people
in behavioral crisis.

00:27:17.780 --> 00:27:20.010
And then they'll spend
up to an hour trying

00:27:20.010 --> 00:27:21.770
to engage them from
outside, giving them

00:27:21.770 --> 00:27:23.750
lots of time and space.

00:27:23.750 --> 00:27:26.840
You all saw in Seattle
a few weeks ago,

00:27:26.840 --> 00:27:29.450
downtown was shut down because
there was a knife-wielding man.

00:27:29.450 --> 00:27:31.741
And there was a confrontation
with the police that took

00:27:31.741 --> 00:27:33.470
two or three hours to resolve.

00:27:33.470 --> 00:27:35.610
They were using, I think,
the greatest tool of all,

00:27:35.610 --> 00:27:37.820
which is patience, you know?

00:27:37.820 --> 00:27:40.520
Giving that time and space
to the community members

00:27:40.520 --> 00:27:41.660
in order to engage.

00:27:41.660 --> 00:27:43.230
But you have to
have the capacity,

00:27:43.230 --> 00:27:45.020
you have to have the
physical resources.

00:27:45.020 --> 00:27:48.230
In King County, the sheriff's
deputies right alone.

00:27:48.230 --> 00:27:49.780
Seattle they ride in pairs.

00:27:49.780 --> 00:27:53.930
