00:30:53.750 --> 00:30:55.750
BARRY FRIEDMAN: Yeah, so
that's a good question.

00:30:55.750 --> 00:31:01.220
So the policing project, we
work with policing agencies all

00:31:01.220 --> 00:31:02.520
the time, and with communities.

00:31:02.520 --> 00:31:04.254
So depending upon
the community, we're

00:31:04.254 --> 00:31:05.420
kind of in a different role.

00:31:05.420 --> 00:31:08.060
In Cleveland, we're working
with the federal monitor doing

00:31:08.060 --> 00:31:10.730
community engagement in terms
of getting the community to have

00:31:10.730 --> 00:31:12.260
input into the monitoring plan.

00:31:12.260 --> 00:31:14.390
They're under a consent
decree following

00:31:14.390 --> 00:31:17.450
Tamir Rice to deal with
use of force issues.

00:31:17.450 --> 00:31:20.480
In Camden, we're there
because the police chief

00:31:20.480 --> 00:31:23.000
asked us to come in and help
him engage with his community,

00:31:23.000 --> 00:31:24.020
and deal with some
of these issues.

00:31:24.020 --> 00:31:25.000
We're setting up a--

00:31:25.000 --> 00:31:27.500
you saw on the slide, a
advisory council in Tucson.

00:31:27.500 --> 00:31:29.470
We're working with the
L.A. Police commission.

00:31:29.470 --> 00:31:31.880
It's the only civilian-run
police department

00:31:31.880 --> 00:31:35.894
in the country to ask the
question to the public, what

00:31:35.894 --> 00:31:37.310
do we do about
body camera footage

00:31:37.310 --> 00:31:39.320
after there's been an
officer-involved shooting?

00:31:39.320 --> 00:31:43.490
And so we often feel like
we're operating in a minefield.

00:31:43.490 --> 00:31:46.496
We talk a lot about
walking a very thin line.

00:31:46.496 --> 00:31:47.870
I'm very careful
about the things

00:31:47.870 --> 00:31:51.260
I say in public because
the public is there,

00:31:51.260 --> 00:31:53.320
the community is there,
but also the police.

00:31:53.320 --> 00:31:56.580
And it's easy to alienate
one or the other.

00:31:56.580 --> 00:31:59.540
But the goal is to try
to bring them together.

00:31:59.540 --> 00:32:01.394
And I try to--

00:32:01.394 --> 00:32:02.810
Ana and I were
talking about this.

00:32:02.810 --> 00:32:05.220
I try to think the best of
people in every situation,

00:32:05.220 --> 00:32:07.640
and assume that they're
acting in good faith,

00:32:07.640 --> 00:32:10.580
and are often in
just bad situations.

00:32:10.580 --> 00:32:15.470
And I have found that if you--
it's slow, slow, painful work.

00:32:15.470 --> 00:32:18.810
It is really remarkable
how hard some of it is.

00:32:18.810 --> 00:32:21.342
But you get these
glimmers of sunlight

00:32:21.342 --> 00:32:23.300
when people are communicating
with one another,

00:32:23.300 --> 00:32:24.600
and progress is being made.

00:32:24.600 --> 00:32:26.995
And the police realize they
can listen to the community,

00:32:26.995 --> 00:32:28.370
and it's not
threatening to them.

00:32:28.370 --> 00:32:30.286
And that the community
actually is supportive,

00:32:30.286 --> 00:32:32.669
and has ideas for how to
do things differently.

00:32:32.669 --> 00:32:35.210
And the community realizes that
the police are not just there

00:32:35.210 --> 00:32:37.100
to terrorize them,
but actually are

00:32:37.100 --> 00:32:39.560
folks who came to the job
originally thinking that they

00:32:39.560 --> 00:32:40.560
would do something good.

00:32:40.560 --> 00:32:42.784
And so that happens too
seldom, but when it happens,

00:32:42.784 --> 00:32:43.950
I think it's pretty magical.

00:32:43.950 --> 00:32:45.354
And that's the idea.

00:32:45.354 --> 00:32:46.770
DEBORAH JACOBS:
If you don't mind,

00:32:46.770 --> 00:32:48.770
I'll also throw in
two cents on that one.

00:32:48.770 --> 00:32:50.930
Hands down, the
hardest part of my job

00:32:50.930 --> 00:32:54.260
is trying to work
both collaboratively

00:32:54.260 --> 00:32:58.460
and adversarialy with
the department I oversee.

00:32:58.460 --> 00:33:01.130
I'm very fortunate because
our Sheriff, John Urquhart,

00:33:01.130 --> 00:33:02.450
is very progressive.

00:33:02.450 --> 00:33:04.730
He, for example, has
taken a strong stand

00:33:04.730 --> 00:33:09.050
about not enforcing civil
immigration enforcement

00:33:09.050 --> 00:33:10.500
for the federal government.

00:33:10.500 --> 00:33:12.770
He also has been
great, progressive

00:33:12.770 --> 00:33:15.400
on drug policy issues.

00:33:15.400 --> 00:33:19.370
But we're-- as I described, we
kind of review what they do.

00:33:19.370 --> 00:33:21.590
So it's like
[CAT FIGHTING NOISES] you know?

00:33:21.590 --> 00:33:25.220
And you have to-- you want
to find your common areas,

00:33:25.220 --> 00:33:29.000
and march those forward, and
also deal with the pain points.

00:33:29.000 --> 00:33:31.982
And people in my field
get fired all the time.

00:33:31.982 --> 00:33:33.690
I don't think I even
have any friends who

00:33:33.690 --> 00:33:35.689
have worked in this field
who haven't been fired

00:33:35.689 --> 00:33:39.530
from their jobs
eventually because you

00:33:39.530 --> 00:33:43.460
have to be pro-community,
and collaborative

00:33:43.460 --> 00:33:45.120
with law enforcement, as well.

00:33:45.120 --> 00:33:47.960
So it's kind of--
it's a struggle,

00:33:47.960 --> 00:33:51.950
and frankly, is calling on
the depths of my maturity,

00:33:51.950 --> 00:33:53.270
to the extent there are any.

00:33:53.270 --> 00:33:54.284
[LAUGHS]

00:33:54.284 --> 00:33:55.700
BARRY FRIEDMAN:
You know, I just--

00:33:55.700 --> 00:33:57.944
if you think about
it, in government--

00:33:57.944 --> 00:33:59.360
and it's important
for what I want

00:33:59.360 --> 00:34:03.710
to say about what the
tech community can offer,

00:34:03.710 --> 00:34:05.489
the front end and the
back end of policing

00:34:05.489 --> 00:34:08.030
should talk to one another, just
like everything else, right?

00:34:08.030 --> 00:34:12.500
So I am party to a lot of
anguished conversations

00:34:12.500 --> 00:34:14.900
with folks that are angry
that police officers have not

00:34:14.900 --> 00:34:18.409
been held accountable, that
they've not been indicted.

00:34:18.409 --> 00:34:20.420
And part of the reason
is because we are not

00:34:20.420 --> 00:34:22.290
clear enough on the front
end about what we expect.

00:34:22.290 --> 00:34:23.820
The standards are
very, very vague.

00:34:23.820 --> 00:34:26.000
So you can have a very
effective back end

00:34:26.000 --> 00:34:28.699
unless you've got a front end
that's got legitimacy to it,

00:34:28.699 --> 00:34:31.080
and that tells people
what's expected of them.

00:34:31.080 --> 00:34:33.560
And by the same token,
what Deborah does,

00:34:33.560 --> 00:34:34.940
she's got exactly
the right model

00:34:34.940 --> 00:34:37.250
going in the sense of,
if you're on the back end

00:34:37.250 --> 00:34:38.874
and you see where
there are problems,

00:34:38.874 --> 00:34:40.790
then that ought to inform
how you want to have

00:34:40.790 --> 00:34:42.830
new policies on the front end.

00:34:42.830 --> 00:34:45.210
And it all ought to work
that way, in a healthy way.

00:34:45.210 --> 00:34:47.674
So even though it's adversarial
and also collaborative,

00:34:47.674 --> 00:34:49.340
that's how we're
supposed to be in terms

00:34:49.340 --> 00:34:51.679
of being self-critical about
what government's doing,

00:34:51.679 --> 00:34:52.790
and then improving it.

00:34:52.790 --> 00:34:57.200
It doesn't happen that way very
often, but that's the idea.

00:34:57.200 --> 00:34:58.900
You going to ask a que-- yeah.

00:34:58.900 --> 00:35:00.140
Or were you just
holding up the--the--[LAUGHS]

00:35:00.140 --> 00:35:02.098
AUDIENCE: Yeah, I'm just
hanging out over here.

00:35:02.098 --> 00:35:02.610
No.

00:35:02.610 --> 00:35:04.026
So first, thanks
for coming today.

00:35:04.026 --> 00:35:06.809
I really enjoyed
both of those talks.

00:35:06.809 --> 00:35:09.350
So I was going to say, I have
a lot of friends that are cops.

00:35:09.350 --> 00:35:12.160
And with everything that's
been happening recently,

00:35:12.160 --> 00:35:15.530
we talk a lot, I guess,
about what they're doing,

00:35:15.530 --> 00:35:18.270
and what the community
thinks about it.

00:35:18.270 --> 00:35:21.155
And one thing that
I've found is,

00:35:21.155 --> 00:35:23.630
they kind of think
that a lot of policies

00:35:23.630 --> 00:35:28.130
that are there to protect
citizens are against them.

00:35:28.130 --> 00:35:30.050
One specific example
that I can think of

00:35:30.050 --> 00:35:35.160
is, in Seattle, you have to pull
someone over only for the thing

00:35:35.160 --> 00:35:37.010
that you're pulling
them over for, which

00:35:37.010 --> 00:35:38.690
is different from other places.

00:35:38.690 --> 00:35:40.107
And that makes sense to me.

00:35:40.107 --> 00:35:41.690
I feel like that's
really good policy.

00:35:41.690 --> 00:35:47.150
But to them, it's like, if
we suspect a guy of some drug

00:35:47.150 --> 00:35:50.270
offense, and then we
see that he's speeding,

00:35:50.270 --> 00:35:52.580
we can't use that as a reason
to pull him over and look

00:35:52.580 --> 00:35:53.490
for something else.

00:35:53.490 --> 00:35:55.340
And it's sort of a--

00:35:55.340 --> 00:35:58.470
to them, it's hurting
them in doing their job.

00:35:58.470 --> 00:36:00.650
And so what I'm
wondering is, is there

00:36:00.650 --> 00:36:02.390
anything being done
to sort of bridge

00:36:02.390 --> 00:36:04.844
that gap where they don't
feel like the policies

00:36:04.844 --> 00:36:06.260
are against them,
and they can see

00:36:06.260 --> 00:36:08.870
the benefit for the community?

00:36:08.870 --> 00:36:13.081
And then also, is the problem
the incentive structure?

00:36:13.081 --> 00:36:13.580
Yeah.

00:36:13.580 --> 00:36:18.695
BARRY FRIEDMAN: So that's
a terrific question.

00:36:18.695 --> 00:36:20.590
We conduct debates
in this country

00:36:20.590 --> 00:36:22.880
in an unbelievably
unhealthy way.

00:36:22.880 --> 00:36:25.820
And it's often you're
pro-cop or anti-cop.

00:36:25.820 --> 00:36:29.390
Or you're-- sometimes I think
it's like you're pro-safety

00:36:29.390 --> 00:36:31.220
and security, or
you're pro-liberty.

00:36:31.220 --> 00:36:35.660
And I always wonder,
you know, I'm both.

00:36:35.660 --> 00:36:37.460
I tell people I have young kids.

00:36:37.460 --> 00:36:40.520
I live near the
World Trade Center.

00:36:40.520 --> 00:36:42.039
I want to be safe and secure.

00:36:42.039 --> 00:36:43.580
I want my kids to
be safe and secure.

00:36:43.580 --> 00:36:46.650
And I also want to live in a
society where we have liberty,

00:36:46.650 --> 00:36:48.540
and we treat one
another respectfully.

00:36:48.540 --> 00:36:52.520
And I hate that we divide the
world up in that other way,

00:36:52.520 --> 00:36:54.080
and then think about
things that way.

00:36:54.080 --> 00:36:59.300
So what the officers are talking
about is, it has become very--

00:36:59.300 --> 00:37:02.060
it became very common
in the United States

00:37:02.060 --> 00:37:03.710
to engage in what
was often referred

00:37:03.710 --> 00:37:05.810
to as proactive policing.

00:37:05.810 --> 00:37:07.190
That meant lots of stops--

00:37:07.190 --> 00:37:10.490
lots of pedestrian stops,
lots of traffic stops.

00:37:10.490 --> 00:37:12.710
And cops will tell you,
they can stop anybody.

00:37:12.710 --> 00:37:14.793
You follow somebody for
just a little bit of time,

00:37:14.793 --> 00:37:16.947
there's 1,000 things
that you could do wrong

00:37:16.947 --> 00:37:17.780
in the vehicle code.

00:37:17.780 --> 00:37:19.470
It's easy to pull people over.

00:37:19.470 --> 00:37:21.710
And then they get
consent to search.

00:37:21.710 --> 00:37:24.680
And I looked at data from L.A.
at one point one quarter--

00:37:24.680 --> 00:37:25.820
I mean, one half of a year.

00:37:25.820 --> 00:37:29.900
And 19,000 some-100 people
were asked to consent,

00:37:29.900 --> 00:37:31.670
and three people didn't.

00:37:31.670 --> 00:37:34.046
So you wonder how
voluntary that consent is.

00:37:34.046 --> 00:37:36.170
Though you do also want to
meet those three people.

00:37:36.170 --> 00:37:38.600
[LAUGHTER]

00:37:38.600 --> 00:37:41.397
And you know, that's a decision
for us to make as a soci--

00:37:41.397 --> 00:37:43.730
I mean, first of all, there
are constitutional problems.

00:37:43.730 --> 00:37:46.280
It's not clear that you should
be pulling over a lot of people

00:37:46.280 --> 00:37:46.870
with no cause.

00:37:46.870 --> 00:37:49.765
The meaning of living in a
liberal democracy like we are

00:37:49.765 --> 00:37:51.640
is that you have a
certain amount of liberty,

00:37:51.640 --> 00:37:53.140
and that shouldn't happen.

00:37:53.140 --> 00:37:55.420
But that's the exact
question, which

00:37:55.420 --> 00:37:57.900
is that we don't
say, how do we want

00:37:57.900 --> 00:38:00.880
to fight crime while we
talk about being worried

00:38:00.880 --> 00:38:01.570
about crime.

00:38:01.570 --> 00:38:03.770
We don't have a conversation
about how part of that.

00:38:03.770 --> 00:38:05.920
And we all ought to be
in that conversation,

00:38:05.920 --> 00:38:07.780
and we should include the
police in the conversation.

00:38:07.780 --> 00:38:09.238
Everywhere we go,
everything we do,

00:38:09.238 --> 00:38:11.110
we hold focus groups
with the officers,

00:38:11.110 --> 00:38:13.284
line officers, the brass.

00:38:13.284 --> 00:38:14.950
They should be part
of the conversation.

00:38:14.950 --> 00:38:16.450
But I hate the
notion that they have

00:38:16.450 --> 00:38:19.120
the ownership over
that question,

00:38:19.120 --> 00:38:21.640
or feel that they have
the ownership over it.

00:38:21.640 --> 00:38:25.210
Remarkable documents sitting
on my desk from the Fraternal

00:38:25.210 --> 00:38:27.430
organization, the
union in Chicago,

00:38:27.430 --> 00:38:30.340
the superintendent in Chicago
in the middle of all the uproar,

00:38:30.340 --> 00:38:32.980
new use of force policy.

00:38:32.980 --> 00:38:34.602
Sends it out to the public to--

00:38:34.602 --> 00:38:37.060
they had a cool online program,
and everybody could kind of

00:38:37.060 --> 00:38:38.680
add comments and edit.

00:38:38.680 --> 00:38:41.650
And the Fraternal
organization was outraged.

00:38:41.650 --> 00:38:44.550
And they sent out this
email that basically said--

00:38:44.550 --> 00:38:47.350
I mean, they used this phrase,
the world's turned upside down.

00:38:47.350 --> 00:38:50.110
The superintendent's taken
our use of force policy,

00:38:50.110 --> 00:38:53.680
and asked the public
what they think.

00:38:53.680 --> 00:38:56.932
And all I could think
was, how crazy is that?

00:38:56.932 --> 00:38:58.390
Asking the people
that you're going

00:38:58.390 --> 00:39:00.970
to use force on what the policy
should be for using force,

00:39:00.970 --> 00:39:01.210
right?

00:39:01.210 --> 00:39:03.040
I mean, it wouldn't
strike any of us as crazy.

00:39:03.040 --> 00:39:04.780
And that's just
something that's broken,

00:39:04.780 --> 00:39:07.880
and that's exactly the thing
that we're trying to fix.

00:39:07.880 --> 00:39:08.810
How to fix it?

00:39:08.810 --> 00:39:10.810
So this will be my
pitch to all of you

00:39:10.810 --> 00:39:13.337
out there about-- so this front
end accountability is really

00:39:13.337 --> 00:39:15.670
difficult because we don't
have any structures for doing

00:39:15.670 --> 00:39:16.545
it the United States.

00:39:16.545 --> 00:39:19.100
We're making it all
up all the time.

00:39:19.100 --> 00:39:20.890
And when you're making
it up all the time,

00:39:20.890 --> 00:39:22.990
there are a lot of questions
that tread into the world

00:39:22.990 --> 00:39:25.281
in which you live, and where
all of you can be helpful.

00:39:25.281 --> 00:39:28.810
So we are working often in
very marginalized communities.

00:39:28.810 --> 00:39:30.850
And there are inadequate
ways to conduct

00:39:30.850 --> 00:39:33.280
participatory democracy,
and to do it in a way

00:39:33.280 --> 00:39:35.517
that people aren't having
to come to a meeting

00:39:35.517 --> 00:39:37.350
when they don't have
time come to a meeting,

00:39:37.350 --> 00:39:38.350
they got kids to take care of.

00:39:38.350 --> 00:39:40.683
And we need to have a easy
way for people to have input.

00:39:40.683 --> 00:39:42.310
And the platforms
aren't very good.

00:39:42.310 --> 00:39:43.810
We want to know if
what we're doing works.

00:39:43.810 --> 00:39:45.560
And to figure out what
you're doing works,

00:39:45.560 --> 00:39:47.350
you need to do a
lot of surveying.

00:39:47.350 --> 00:39:49.180
And the platforms for--

00:39:49.180 --> 00:39:51.580
there aren't platforms that
allow police departments

00:39:51.580 --> 00:39:55.050
to easily go in and get
into their geo-coded parts

00:39:55.050 --> 00:39:56.800
of their community,
and say, how we doing?

00:39:56.800 --> 00:39:58.600
How's the new policy
affecting people?

00:39:58.600 --> 00:40:00.120
To test legitimacy,
to test trust,

00:40:00.120 --> 00:40:01.870
so that we can see
over time whether we're

00:40:01.870 --> 00:40:02.800
making any progress.

00:40:02.800 --> 00:40:04.750
Just doesn't exist.

00:40:04.750 --> 00:40:05.549
Huge data needs.

00:40:05.549 --> 00:40:07.090
So one of the things
we're looking at

00:40:07.090 --> 00:40:10.476
is, there are measures
of the impacts

00:40:10.476 --> 00:40:12.100
of policing that
people just have never

00:40:12.100 --> 00:40:13.310
thought about very much.

00:40:13.310 --> 00:40:16.210
So we want to kind of go in
and ask in communities where

00:40:16.210 --> 00:40:18.900
there's been this kind
of proactive policing,

00:40:18.900 --> 00:40:21.250
are there effects
on public health?

00:40:21.250 --> 00:40:22.540
What about education rates?

00:40:22.540 --> 00:40:24.790
Drop out?

00:40:24.790 --> 00:40:27.910
Obviously offending and arrests?

00:40:27.910 --> 00:40:29.890
And so there are
lots of opportunities

00:40:29.890 --> 00:40:30.982
to engage in this project.

00:40:30.982 --> 00:40:33.190
I mean, I commend Deborah
for all the suggestions she

00:40:33.190 --> 00:40:35.020
had locally, but
those same problems

00:40:35.020 --> 00:40:37.812
are multiplied through 18,000
different policing agencies.

00:40:37.812 --> 00:40:39.520
I don't know if you
want to add anything.

00:40:39.520 --> 00:40:40.330
I just went on and
on there, sorry.

00:40:40.330 --> 00:40:41.270
DEBORAH JACOBS:
I'll just throw in

00:40:41.270 --> 00:40:43.900
that I think we confront the
same kind of problem that we

00:40:43.900 --> 00:40:46.000
confront with other groups
that are essentially

00:40:46.000 --> 00:40:48.280
segregated from one
another, and that

00:40:48.280 --> 00:40:49.950
is that we don't
know each other,

00:40:49.950 --> 00:40:52.690
and we don't come into
each other's territory--

00:40:52.690 --> 00:40:55.090
whether it's black and
white, or cops and civilians,

00:40:55.090 --> 00:40:56.450
or whatever it is.

00:40:56.450 --> 00:40:58.570
And so I think it's incumbent
upon those of us who

00:40:58.570 --> 00:41:00.520
care about those things
to take those steps,

00:41:00.520 --> 00:41:03.000
and try to meet each
other where we are.

00:41:03.000 --> 00:41:06.160
From my office specifically,
we administrate

00:41:06.160 --> 00:41:08.320
an alternative
dispute resolution.

00:41:08.320 --> 00:41:10.960
I would way rather
see a cop spend

00:41:10.960 --> 00:41:13.500
an hour in the room with
a facilitator talking

00:41:13.500 --> 00:41:15.930
to a person who had a
complaint against them

00:41:15.930 --> 00:41:17.920
than get a five day
suspension because I think

00:41:17.920 --> 00:41:19.510
it's worth that much more.

00:41:19.510 --> 00:41:22.852
I kind of think we need a
truth and reconciliation--

00:41:22.852 --> 00:41:24.310
I don't what that
looks like, but I

00:41:24.310 --> 00:41:27.770
think there's enough damage
that really stems from slavery

00:41:27.770 --> 00:41:31.960
in particular that
we have more dialogue

00:41:31.960 --> 00:41:35.230
to conduct before we're
going to be able to meet.

00:41:35.230 --> 00:41:37.189
But someone like
you is invaluable.

00:41:37.189 --> 00:41:38.980
You know some of these
people, but you also

00:41:38.980 --> 00:41:41.240
have outside perspectives.

00:41:41.240 --> 00:41:43.470
You can take your
bubble and their bubble,

00:41:43.470 --> 00:41:44.620
and make a bubble bath.

00:41:44.620 --> 00:41:46.810
[LAUGHTER]

00:41:46.810 --> 00:41:48.430
BARRY FRIEDMAN: I love that.

00:41:48.430 --> 00:41:49.431
I'm going to steal that.

00:41:49.431 --> 00:41:50.680
DEBORAH JACOBS: No, you can't.

00:41:50.680 --> 00:41:51.370
[LAUGHTER]

00:41:51.370 --> 00:41:53.110
BARRY FRIEDMAN: It may not work
as well if I do the bubble bath

00:41:53.110 --> 00:41:54.190
thing, but yeah.

00:41:54.190 --> 00:41:56.360
AUDIENCE: So all this talk--
first, the great talk,

00:41:56.360 --> 00:41:56.860
by the way.

00:41:56.860 --> 00:41:58.410
Thanks for both of
you for coming--

00:41:58.410 --> 00:41:59.493
to both of you for coming.

00:41:59.493 --> 00:42:03.340
So all this talk
is about expanding

00:42:03.340 --> 00:42:07.540
the oversight of the police
over the law enforcement.

00:42:07.540 --> 00:42:08.360
And one of my--

00:42:08.360 --> 00:42:10.990
the concerns I have
is that there's

00:42:10.990 --> 00:42:15.460
no equal oversight over the
citizens in terms of organized

00:42:15.460 --> 00:42:16.930
crime, for instance.

00:42:16.930 --> 00:42:19.210
In other words,
we're restricting,

00:42:19.210 --> 00:42:20.980
we are tying the
hands of the police,

00:42:20.980 --> 00:42:24.040
but we are opening the hands
of the organized crime.

00:42:24.040 --> 00:42:29.380
And what are your thoughts about
expanding the oversight one

00:42:29.380 --> 00:42:32.660
way or another over
suspected criminals?

00:42:32.660 --> 00:42:36.680
So maybe required that the
information, where they go,

00:42:36.680 --> 00:42:39.670
is just as public as a
policeman, or anything

00:42:39.670 --> 00:42:43.374
like that so that we can kind
of counter to the other trend,

00:42:43.374 --> 00:42:45.040
that actually, as we
weaken the police--

00:42:45.040 --> 00:42:46.930
and I've seen that
in other societies.

00:42:46.930 --> 00:42:50.280
The police weakens, and the
organized crime strengthens.

00:42:50.280 --> 00:42:51.200
So--

00:42:51.200 --> 00:42:54.380
BARRY FRIEDMAN: So
that's a hard question.

00:42:54.380 --> 00:42:56.200
It's particularly
difficult in part

00:42:56.200 --> 00:42:58.540
because we don't
empirically know

00:42:58.540 --> 00:43:03.220
whether we're empowering
criminals and limiting

00:43:03.220 --> 00:43:06.050
the police, and where the
optimal level of enforcement

00:43:06.050 --> 00:43:06.550
is.

00:43:06.550 --> 00:43:08.924
I mean, you're exactly right--
there's some optimal level

00:43:08.924 --> 00:43:09.970
of enforcement, right?

00:43:09.970 --> 00:43:12.560
The law and economics
folks around me would say,

00:43:12.560 --> 00:43:15.520
we just have to figure out the
optimal level of enforcement.

00:43:15.520 --> 00:43:16.978
By the way, I just
want to say, I'm

00:43:16.978 --> 00:43:20.530
not sure I want to
limit the police more.

00:43:20.530 --> 00:43:22.810
I want to change the nature
of what we call oversight.

00:43:22.810 --> 00:43:24.476
In fact, I don't like
the word oversight

00:43:24.476 --> 00:43:26.710
for a lot of what
we do, I mean, you

00:43:26.710 --> 00:43:29.115
know Deborah does oversight,
but on the front end,

00:43:29.115 --> 00:43:30.490
I don't think of
it as oversight.

00:43:30.490 --> 00:43:34.150
I think of it as
collaborating on figuring out

00:43:34.150 --> 00:43:37.660
what the rules should be for
exactly what you're asking.

00:43:37.660 --> 00:43:39.520
The other thing is,
technology has actually

00:43:39.520 --> 00:43:41.031
addressed some of that problem.

00:43:41.031 --> 00:43:43.030
So this is the question
you were going to plant,

00:43:43.030 --> 00:43:44.290
and I'm now going to
relieve you of planting it

00:43:44.290 --> 00:43:44.990
[LAUGHTER]

00:43:44.990 --> 00:43:47.050
But so the-- guess we're
not supposed to let

00:43:47.050 --> 00:43:48.670
people know that, either.

00:43:48.670 --> 00:43:51.520
So the policing's
changed dramatically

00:43:51.520 --> 00:43:52.540
in the last 30 years.

00:43:52.540 --> 00:43:54.081
And I don't think
anybody noticed it,

00:43:54.081 --> 00:43:56.310
just like technology
swept over all of us,

00:43:56.310 --> 00:43:59.070
and we just kind of
adapted, but didn't--

00:43:59.070 --> 00:44:00.440
then you have your whoa moment.

00:44:00.440 --> 00:44:03.020
So policing used to be
all about suspicion,

00:44:03.020 --> 00:44:05.960
or a lot about suspicion,
which was that you knew--

00:44:05.960 --> 00:44:08.030
you had a reason to
think that somebody

00:44:08.030 --> 00:44:10.790
was doing something wrong,
or had done something wrong.

00:44:10.790 --> 00:44:14.390
And the Constitution was written
to focus on suspicion that way.

00:44:14.390 --> 00:44:16.387
So we think about
probable cause, right?

00:44:16.387 --> 00:44:17.720
Why is the government after you?

00:44:17.720 --> 00:44:20.390
Because we have enough facts,
probable cause, to think

00:44:20.390 --> 00:44:21.650
you've done something wrong.

00:44:21.650 --> 00:44:24.124
Enough to justify getting
a warrant to search you.

00:44:24.124 --> 00:44:25.790
And it was a very
suspicion-based model.

00:44:25.790 --> 00:44:28.550
But if you think about the
way that policing looks today,

00:44:28.550 --> 00:44:29.420
it's very different.

00:44:29.420 --> 00:44:31.160
It's a deterrent-based
model, which

00:44:31.160 --> 00:44:33.470
is that we're going to conduct
sufficient surveillance

00:44:33.470 --> 00:44:36.422
over all of society that
we've got an eye on you.

00:44:36.422 --> 00:44:37.880
And you know we
have an eye on you.

00:44:37.880 --> 00:44:39.172
And hopefully-- you especially.

00:44:39.172 --> 00:44:40.379
We're going to behave, right?

00:44:40.379 --> 00:44:41.120
[LAUGHTER]

00:44:41.120 --> 00:44:44.130
And so we're all going
to pay attention.

00:44:44.130 --> 00:44:46.850
And so we're going to collect
everybody's telephone metadata.

00:44:46.850 --> 00:44:49.640
And it's not just being
used for national security.

00:44:49.640 --> 00:44:52.190
That information can
be queried by the FBI.

00:44:52.190 --> 00:44:55.160
It's a real problem in the law.

00:44:55.160 --> 00:44:56.750
We're going to have
airport security,

00:44:56.750 --> 00:44:57.560
and we're just going
to get everybody

00:44:57.560 --> 00:44:58.684
to march through it, right?

00:44:58.684 --> 00:45:01.590
There's no cause to think
anybody's got a weapon, we just

00:45:01.590 --> 00:45:03.371
we spent a ton of
money on the theory

00:45:03.371 --> 00:45:05.870
that we're going to keep people
from showing up with weapons

00:45:05.870 --> 00:45:06.900
in the first place.

00:45:06.900 --> 00:45:10.779
And so we actually have a ton
of surveillance right now.

00:45:10.779 --> 00:45:13.320
I mean, one of the big questions
is location-tracking, right?

00:45:13.320 --> 00:45:15.800
We're all telling the police
where we are with our phones

00:45:15.800 --> 00:45:16.710
at every moment.

00:45:16.710 --> 00:45:18.530
And we have inadequate
legal controls

00:45:18.530 --> 00:45:19.710
on getting that information.

00:45:19.710 --> 00:45:21.624
So I'm not sure where
the balance is, and I

00:45:21.624 --> 00:45:22.790
don't think any of us knows.

00:45:22.790 --> 00:45:24.950
Because we don't tend
to think about things

00:45:24.950 --> 00:45:28.710
in this world in any kind of
scientific, careful, thoughtful

00:45:28.710 --> 00:45:29.210
way.

00:45:29.210 --> 00:45:30.793
We just have a lot
of public rhetoric.

00:45:30.793 --> 00:45:34.040
And I think that's a shame,
because I want us to be free,

00:45:34.040 --> 00:45:35.690
and I want us to be safe.

00:45:35.690 --> 00:45:38.600
And I published a piece
in the Outlook section

00:45:38.600 --> 00:45:41.090
of the Washington Post
a few weeks ago that--

00:45:41.090 --> 00:45:43.910
just to ask the question,
we spent $100 billion a year

00:45:43.910 --> 00:45:46.700
on public safety, ought
we to know what works?

00:45:46.700 --> 00:45:48.720
So I'm with you,
I want to be safe.

00:45:48.720 --> 00:45:51.011
But I want to have a better
understanding of, actually,

00:45:51.011 --> 00:45:52.440
where we are with that.

00:45:52.440 --> 00:45:53.520
Thank you.

00:45:53.520 --> 00:45:54.520
AUDIENCE: Oh, thank you.

00:45:54.520 --> 00:45:56.110
Thank you for coming.

00:45:56.110 --> 00:45:58.880
So my question is about--

00:45:58.880 --> 00:46:01.110
you started your lecture
with a bunch of examples

00:46:01.110 --> 00:46:03.420
where police clearly
misbehaved, or we

00:46:03.420 --> 00:46:06.810
would call it bad policing,
and extreme examples.

00:46:06.810 --> 00:46:10.580
What's the mental model that
you have about those cases?

00:46:10.580 --> 00:46:11.880
Few bad apples?

00:46:11.880 --> 00:46:12.630
Few bad districts?

00:46:12.630 --> 00:46:12.935
BARRY FRIEDMAN: Yeah, no.

00:46:12.935 --> 00:46:13.640
No.

00:46:13.640 --> 00:46:15.960
AUDIENCE: Is it most of
the districts are bad?

00:46:15.960 --> 00:46:16.185
What's the distribution, there?

00:46:16.185 --> 00:46:17.518
BARRY FRIEDMAN: It's bad policy.

00:46:17.518 --> 00:46:18.540
It's bad policy.

00:46:18.540 --> 00:46:21.100
So-- and it's suboptimal policy.

00:46:21.100 --> 00:46:22.080
So that's the point.

00:46:22.080 --> 00:46:29.100
So we-- a lot of the problems
that I showed at the beginning,

00:46:29.100 --> 00:46:31.380
I can walk you back
through and show you

00:46:31.380 --> 00:46:35.680
how a more sensible policy
would have avoided that problem.

00:46:35.680 --> 00:46:39.810
And if you thought that some
of those were problems--

00:46:39.810 --> 00:46:41.310
I mean, just think
about the amount

00:46:41.310 --> 00:46:47.070
of time and loss of human
dignity and discomfort

00:46:47.070 --> 00:46:50.310
that's associated with forcibly
catheterizing somebody, right?

00:46:50.310 --> 00:46:51.960
So I don't know if
we ever want to do.

00:46:51.960 --> 00:46:53.070
And I'm not sure
that we ever want

00:46:53.070 --> 00:46:55.320
to do it for the crime of
driving under the influence.

00:46:55.320 --> 00:46:57.736
And if you were going to get
me to thinking we should ever

00:46:57.736 --> 00:46:59.370
do it, we maybe should
do it if there's

00:46:59.370 --> 00:47:02.370
a tragic accident, right?

00:47:02.370 --> 00:47:05.100
But that's heavy-handed
police behavior,

00:47:05.100 --> 00:47:08.760
and it's taking a cop
off of their patrol

00:47:08.760 --> 00:47:11.231
where they'd be, maybe, missing
something far more serious,

00:47:11.231 --> 00:47:11.730
right?

00:47:11.730 --> 00:47:15.180
And so the police
shootings, every one

00:47:15.180 --> 00:47:17.250
of which is an
extraordinary tragedy--

00:47:17.250 --> 00:47:19.170
and I just want to
point something out

00:47:19.170 --> 00:47:21.960
to you, which is that we
view the people who were shot

00:47:21.960 --> 00:47:25.200
and their families as the
center of that tragedy, which

00:47:25.200 --> 00:47:26.730
is exactly right.

00:47:26.730 --> 00:47:29.490
But we often don't think
about the fact that--

00:47:29.490 --> 00:47:32.512
and cops will tell you
this, that the cop who shot

00:47:32.512 --> 00:47:33.720
somebody's life is destroyed.

00:47:33.720 --> 00:47:35.636
And sometimes it's
justified, but their life's

00:47:35.636 --> 00:47:38.580
still completely turned
upside down by having done it.

00:47:38.580 --> 00:47:40.510
We don't want those
things to happen.

00:47:40.510 --> 00:47:43.350
And so instead of just focusing
on who we're going to punish,

00:47:43.350 --> 00:47:44.730
we should be asking the
question, how are we going

00:47:44.730 --> 00:47:46.110
to avoid it in the first place?

00:47:46.110 --> 00:47:47.790
It's a suboptimal policy, right?

00:47:47.790 --> 00:47:50.250
And so-- I mean, that's
what I'm all about,

00:47:50.250 --> 00:47:54.450
is data and optimization.

00:47:54.450 --> 00:47:56.550
And that isn't how we've
approached policing.

00:47:56.550 --> 00:47:58.260
It's not how we've approached
technology in policing.

00:47:58.260 --> 00:48:00.030
I mean, Deborah was
talking about this.

00:48:00.030 --> 00:48:03.030
What happens is, what-agency's
got a new gadget,

00:48:03.030 --> 00:48:04.680
so then the next
agency wants it.

00:48:04.680 --> 00:48:06.263
And they're not
thinking, do I already

00:48:06.263 --> 00:48:07.576
have something that does that?

00:48:07.576 --> 00:48:09.450
Am I thinking about how
the data is getting--

00:48:09.450 --> 00:48:11.130
what the cost of storing
the data is going to be,

00:48:11.130 --> 00:48:12.510
how I'm going to use the data?

00:48:12.510 --> 00:48:15.390
So it's exactly
the right question.

00:48:15.390 --> 00:48:18.240
And my soapbox, I'm
sorry, is that I

00:48:18.240 --> 00:48:21.405
think that we should stop
always looking on the back end,

00:48:21.405 --> 00:48:23.626
and looking for blame when
things go wrong, and say,

00:48:23.626 --> 00:48:25.500
let's optimize policy
so they don't go wrong.

00:48:25.500 --> 00:48:27.376
And we're actually
getting things right.

00:48:27.376 --> 00:48:28.626
AUDIENCE: I get that argument.

00:48:28.626 --> 00:48:31.350
My question is a little
bit more specific.

00:48:31.350 --> 00:48:35.188
When I walk into average
department in the country,

00:48:35.188 --> 00:48:36.330
would I observe--

00:48:36.330 --> 00:48:37.865
what's the extent
I would see it?

00:48:37.865 --> 00:48:40.360
Are there really
few bad departments?

00:48:40.360 --> 00:48:41.197
Most of them are?

00:48:41.197 --> 00:48:44.060
I'm using term
bad loosely, here.

00:48:44.060 --> 00:48:46.359
BARRY FRIEDMAN: Yeah, I get it.

00:48:46.359 --> 00:48:47.400
What's that distribution?

00:48:47.400 --> 00:48:50.598
Are we trying to fix
few localized problems,

00:48:50.598 --> 00:48:52.837
or is it universally
you pretty much

00:48:52.837 --> 00:48:54.494
have to fix the whole system?

00:48:54.494 --> 00:48:55.470
What's the--

00:48:55.470 --> 00:48:56.900
DEBORAH JACOBS: I'm going to
answer a little bit similarly--

00:48:56.900 --> 00:48:58.110
AUDIENCE: And it's subjective,
I understand very--

00:48:58.110 --> 00:48:58.670
DEBORAH JACOBS: Yeah.

00:48:58.670 --> 00:49:00.169
So one thing I would
say is, I don't

00:49:00.169 --> 00:49:02.960
think there are bad apples, I
think there are bad orchards.

00:49:02.960 --> 00:49:05.660
And what makes up the orchard
are some of the things

00:49:05.660 --> 00:49:07.922
that Barry mentioned--

00:49:07.922 --> 00:49:09.380
what kind of policies
are in place?

00:49:09.380 --> 00:49:10.830
What kind of
training is in place?

00:49:10.830 --> 00:49:13.250
And all those things contribute
to the ultimate thing,

00:49:13.250 --> 00:49:15.120
which is the culture.

00:49:15.120 --> 00:49:17.580
What is the culture
of the department?

00:49:17.580 --> 00:49:24.440
And so for the most part, I
think that police departments

00:49:24.440 --> 00:49:28.640
that have not had the benefit of
the sunlight shining upon them,

00:49:28.640 --> 00:49:31.580
whether through litigation,
the DOJ, civilian oversight,

00:49:31.580 --> 00:49:32.960
whatever it might be--

00:49:32.960 --> 00:49:35.300
I think most of them
are problematic.

00:49:35.300 --> 00:49:37.700
Not because they've done
something bad already,

00:49:37.700 --> 00:49:41.300
but because they don't have the
policies and training in place

00:49:41.300 --> 00:49:43.430
to make sure it doesn't happen.

00:49:43.430 --> 00:49:45.950
And when a shooting
happens, they'll

00:49:45.950 --> 00:49:48.995
land in-- so one of the issues
that [? Yves ?] and I just

00:49:48.995 --> 00:49:52.940
talked about a little
earlier, on October 21, 2016,

00:49:52.940 --> 00:49:56.480
a woman was killed by King
County sheriff's deputies

00:49:56.480 --> 00:49:58.880
on the Muckleshoot
Indian Reservation.

00:49:58.880 --> 00:50:00.470
They were-- it was
a wellness call.

00:50:00.470 --> 00:50:03.370
She was suicidal, and they were
coming in response to that.

00:50:03.370 --> 00:50:05.190
And things went terribly wrong.

00:50:05.190 --> 00:50:06.965
There was going to be
an inquest in Kent.

00:50:06.965 --> 00:50:08.445
It starts May 22.

00:50:08.445 --> 00:50:10.820
And what they're going to do--
the purpose of an inquest,

00:50:10.820 --> 00:50:12.800
which is used very
few jurisdictions,

00:50:12.800 --> 00:50:15.500
but King County is one of
them, is to get the truth out

00:50:15.500 --> 00:50:16.100
under oath.

00:50:16.100 --> 00:50:17.380
What happened?

00:50:17.380 --> 00:50:20.330
But citizens find that
process very dissatisfying

00:50:20.330 --> 00:50:23.816
because they get out what
happened, and then what next?

00:50:23.816 --> 00:50:25.190
But as they look
at that, they're

00:50:25.190 --> 00:50:28.380
going to look--
was it justifiable?

00:50:28.380 --> 00:50:31.790
But the lens we need to
have is, was it preventable?

00:50:31.790 --> 00:50:34.350
And so when I look at a
department, is it good,

00:50:34.350 --> 00:50:35.150
is it bad?

00:50:35.150 --> 00:50:37.010
What policies and
training do they

00:50:37.010 --> 00:50:40.155
have in place to prevent the
most common kinds of tragedies?

00:50:40.155 --> 00:50:42.530
And I would posit-- and I
don't have the numbers on this,

00:50:42.530 --> 00:50:46.730
but that the mental health or
behavioral health crises stuff

00:50:46.730 --> 00:50:49.790
is the key place where we
need to be focusing resources.

00:50:49.790 --> 00:50:52.910
Because that is such a breadth
of what they deal with.

00:50:52.910 --> 00:50:54.990
Also related to some
comments you made,

00:50:54.990 --> 00:50:57.900
I want to say that we as
a society need to decide--

00:50:57.900 --> 00:51:01.220
do we want police to
enforce minor things?

00:51:01.220 --> 00:51:03.740
Do we want them to stop Michael
Brown for crossing-- walking

00:51:03.740 --> 00:51:04.989
down the middle of the street?

00:51:04.989 --> 00:51:06.710
Sandra Bland for her
broken taillight?

00:51:06.710 --> 00:51:09.800
Eric Garner for doing
whatever he was doing,

00:51:09.800 --> 00:51:11.270
hanging out on the streets?

00:51:11.270 --> 00:51:12.830
My answer is no.

00:51:12.830 --> 00:51:14.241
I think we have
over-enforcement.

00:51:14.241 --> 00:51:16.490
But then what happens to
those quality of life things?

00:51:16.490 --> 00:51:17.690
How do we address those?

00:51:17.690 --> 00:51:21.060
Because we do care
about them, we all do.

00:51:21.060 --> 00:51:23.090
We have to come up
with other systems.

00:51:23.090 --> 00:51:25.340
And we can't keep
recruiting people

00:51:25.340 --> 00:51:29.330
to be armed cops jumping
out of helicopters when

00:51:29.330 --> 00:51:32.080
actually they're social
workers, that's what the job is.

00:51:32.080 --> 00:51:34.040
So rethinking the
job description

00:51:34.040 --> 00:51:35.450
seems critically
important to me.

00:51:35.450 --> 00:51:38.030
And then hiring on that basis,
and having the community

00:51:38.030 --> 00:51:40.722
understand that what
you don't want enforced,

00:51:40.722 --> 00:51:42.680
we're going to have to
find another answer for,

00:51:42.680 --> 00:51:45.770
whether it's something
you lobby for in Olympia,

00:51:45.770 --> 00:51:48.300
or something that you
implement as a community.

00:51:48.300 --> 00:51:49.816
But a lot of that rests with us.

00:51:49.816 --> 00:51:51.440
We've put these
problems at their feet,

00:51:51.440 --> 00:51:53.730
and they're not trained or
equipped to deal with them.

00:51:53.730 --> 00:51:54.770
BARRY FRIEDMAN: I'm going to
give you just a slightly more

00:51:54.770 --> 00:51:56.550
precise answer
because I appreciate

00:51:56.550 --> 00:51:57.800
the precision of the question.

00:51:57.800 --> 00:51:59.510
So it's kind of remarkable.

00:51:59.510 --> 00:52:01.580
So the NYPD has about
35,000 officers.

00:52:01.580 --> 00:52:04.820
There are plenty of departments
that have one or two officers.

00:52:04.820 --> 00:52:06.970
I think the median in
the country of the 18,000

00:52:06.970 --> 00:52:08.560
departments is 10 officers.

00:52:08.560 --> 00:52:10.490
So it's quite a distribution.

00:52:13.220 --> 00:52:15.800
What surprises you when
you get into policing

00:52:15.800 --> 00:52:20.510
is how it's kind of like
you're walking into the past,

00:52:20.510 --> 00:52:22.460
and how things
haven't moved along.

00:52:22.460 --> 00:52:25.200
And so again, I don't
think they're bad.

00:52:25.200 --> 00:52:26.420
They're not modernized.

00:52:26.420 --> 00:52:28.350
There's been nothing
to cause modernization.

00:52:28.350 --> 00:52:30.530
And to the contrary,
what happens is,

00:52:30.530 --> 00:52:34.100
we'll starve departments
for cash sometimes,

00:52:34.100 --> 00:52:37.050
or it's just used in bad ways.

00:52:37.050 --> 00:52:40.280
And here's another thing, this
is a money-making thing here

00:52:40.280 --> 00:52:40.800
at Google.

00:52:40.800 --> 00:52:43.640
So there's a lot of talk
about transparency and data,

00:52:43.640 --> 00:52:45.660
and we don't have
data on policing.

00:52:45.660 --> 00:52:48.260
So it's hard to have data
on 18,000 separate entities.

00:52:48.260 --> 00:52:50.222
That's tough to do.

00:52:50.222 --> 00:52:51.180
But one of the reason--

00:52:51.180 --> 00:52:52.400
so the story we
tell is-- well, we

00:52:52.400 --> 00:52:53.270
don't have data
because the police

00:52:53.270 --> 00:52:53.900
don't want to give it up.

00:52:53.900 --> 00:52:56.330
I tell that story in the
first few pages of my book.

00:52:56.330 --> 00:52:58.040
I believe that to be true.

00:52:58.040 --> 00:53:00.940
But a lot of it is just
an embarrassment of data

00:53:00.940 --> 00:53:02.540
in the sense of, they don't--

00:53:02.540 --> 00:53:04.340
we decided that we
were curious about stop

00:53:04.340 --> 00:53:06.260
data, demographic stop data.

00:53:06.260 --> 00:53:07.610
And where would we get it?

00:53:07.610 --> 00:53:09.250
Well, there are some
departments under court order,

00:53:09.250 --> 00:53:10.850
so we'll just call them up
and see if they'll share it,

00:53:10.850 --> 00:53:12.050
or they're supposed to share it.

00:53:12.050 --> 00:53:13.280
We literally called
up some departments,

00:53:13.280 --> 00:53:14.988
and they said, yeah,
we'll get it to you.

00:53:14.988 --> 00:53:16.025
What's your fax number?

00:53:16.025 --> 00:53:18.950
And they're ready to fax over
their sheet of their figures.

00:53:18.950 --> 00:53:20.990
And so I actually
think that we'd

00:53:20.990 --> 00:53:24.320
have so much more policing data
if we had the tools developed

00:53:24.320 --> 00:53:25.670
to collect the data.

00:53:25.670 --> 00:53:27.950
And I think there's a real
financial opportunity here,

00:53:27.950 --> 00:53:29.783
which is that there are
18,000 departments--

00:53:29.783 --> 00:53:32.030
and I think they would use
many similar platforms,

00:53:32.030 --> 00:53:33.770
and then we would
have unified data.

00:53:33.770 --> 00:53:36.020
But it's really a--

00:53:36.020 --> 00:53:37.580
I mean, there are
some bad apples,

00:53:37.580 --> 00:53:38.930
but that's not the right story.

00:53:38.930 --> 00:53:43.721
It's just where
modernization didn't happen.

00:53:43.721 --> 00:53:44.570
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:53:44.570 --> 00:53:46.241
BARRY FRIEDMAN: Thank you.

00:53:46.241 --> 00:53:47.780
You want to stop us now.

00:53:47.780 --> 00:53:49.100
Stop us before we kill again.

00:53:49.100 --> 00:53:49.865
[LAUGHTER]

00:53:49.865 --> 00:53:51.490
AUDIENCE: Thank you
so much for coming.

00:53:51.490 --> 00:53:53.115
BARRY FRIEDMAN: Thank
you guys, really.

00:53:53.115 --> 00:53:54.330
[APPLAUSE]

00:53:54.330 --> 00:53:54.830
Thank

00:53:54.830 --> 00:53:56.380
you.

